{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-04252/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-04252"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:42:52"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["close-up"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["eye-level"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, handheld, pan"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man leans to look out of a door's peephole."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-04252","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-04252"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1/309d29c3-da9f-49ae-aa8f-f147186e9771","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T19:32:43.833Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Michael Hardwick writes, “In <em>Phantom Thread</em>, Anderson exposes the great mystery of Hitchcock’s formula, his unique marriage of melodrama and psychoanalysis, for the silliness that it is” (Hardwick, Talking ‘Cure’”). Indeed, the Freudian elements of the film are dialed up to an extreme, from Reynolds’s mommy issues driving his unusual appetites to the codependency that develops between the tailor and his muse. Here, in this shot, Reynolds bursts with energy to catch a glimpse of Alma through the peephole. Sima Movaghati has identified this moment as an allusion to a moment in <em>Bluebeard</em> (1944) when “the puppeteer Gaston Morrell secretly watches his muse and victim, Lucille Lutien, through a peephole” (Movaghati, “Bluebeard Meets Ivy,” 724).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04252/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:834.6702557200539,123.31090174966363,794.6164199192461,718.384925975774"}}}]}]}]}